<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>He said Mama Winnie had been a full member of the church for a long time. “She loved church and every Easter she was here. She donated a cow every Easter,” he said.The reverend said the nation had lost a true leader and he would always remember her for her good heart and love of the people. “Every time she arrived, she would hug and kiss everyone. I knew when she came, I would get a hug and a kiss.” He said last year, after a number of women were killed, Mama Winnie organised a prayer session at Dobsonville Stadium. “Different churches and taxi owners were there. It was great. “That alone showed Mama cared for us as a nation,” he said. The reverend said the church was planning her memorial service on Sunday but were still waiting for confirmation from the family. “We pass our deepest condolences to the family and the nation as a whole.” Madikizela-Mandela, who was known around the world for her fight against apartheid, died at Netcare Milpark Hospital on Monday, aged 81. She had been in and out of hospital since the start of the year and died peacefully, surrounded by family and loved ones. Her funeral service will be held at Orlando Stadium on 14 April.